==French==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|frm|fr}}, from {{term|aborder|lang=frm}}, from {{etyl|fro|fr}} {{term|aborder||to hit a ship in order to board it|lang=fro}}, from {{term|bord||side of a ship, edge|lang=fro}}, of {{etyl|gem|fr}} origin, from Old Low {{etyl|frk|fr}} {{recons|bord|bord|side of a ship or vessel|lang=frk|sc=Latn}}, from {{proto|gem-pro|burdan|edge, border, side|lang=fr}}, from {{proto|ine-pro|bheredh-|to cut|lang=fr}}. Cognate with {{etyl|goh|-}} {{term|bort||edge, rim, rand|lang=goh}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|bord||ship, side of a ship|lang=ang}}, {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|borð||edge, side of a vessel|lang=non}}. More at {{l|en|board}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|Fr-abord.ogg|Audio}}

===Noun===
{{fr-noun|m}}

# {{literary|lang=fr}} The [[manner]] with which one acts in the [[presence]] of another person or persons, especially in a first [[encounter]].
# {{rare|lang=fr}} The [[surrounding]]s of a place.
# {{archaic|lang=fr}} [[arrival|Arrival]] or [[accessibility]] by water.

====Usage notes====
* In the sense "surroundings", the word is almost always a [[pluralia tantum]].
* The sense "manner of acting" is usually now perceived as a backformation from {{term|aborder||to approach}}, and is most common in the expression {{term||être [[d'un abord]]}} and variations of it.

